By Matt Groff
Asst. News Editor

Pitt's $8.5 million purchase of the
Masonic Temple will likely become
home to the special collections divi-
sion of the University Library System,
according to Associate Vice-
Chancellor for Facilities Management
Tom Hussey.

“The reason the administration
bought the building was the need for
library space,” Hussey said.

Hussey said the. building, which Pitt
bought on Dec. 25, 1995, measures
approximately 16(),()()() square feet.
The size of the Temple, which is
located on Fifth Avenue across from
the Cathedral of Learning, will most
likely allow the university to utilize it
in other ways.

"Of course, many other groups
have expressed an interest in space,
but the. administration is looking into
who should get it,” Hussey said.

Hussey said that the provost’s office
is in charge of planning the specific
utili7.ation of the Masonic Temple
space. Bob Pack, who is handling the
matter in the provost’s office, could
not be reached for comment.

According to Hussey, Pitt has
signed an agreement whereby it will
share the building’s expenses with
the Masons for the next two years.

“In return, the Masons will be given
first priority to use the building dur-
ing that time,” Hussey said, emphasiz-
ing that “Pitt owns the building 100
percent.”

Hussey said the Masons expect to
find a new building within the next
two years.

