By Cameron Harvey
Staff Writer

Hoping to avoid tangling with
the American Civil Liberties
Union this year, the Pitt Program
Council has established a series
of requirements for eligibility in
its upcoming 1994 Student Art
Show.

Last year, Pitt student David
Brown, at that time a third—year
student, submitted a painting of a
penis tree entitled, “There's no
place like Hollidaysburg".

The PPC Art Committee, how-
ever, tried to keep the painting
from being displayed last year
because they found it to be too
offensive for the university's envi-
ronment.

Vice Chancellor of Student

Affairs William Harmon defended
the move, saying “There is no
attempt at censorship, but there is
an attempt at good taste.”

The American Civil Liberties
Union took up Brown’s issue and
eventually won, clearing the way
for the painting to be displayed.

This year, the PPC is prepared
to avoid a repeat of last year’s
controversy.

As a part of the application
process, six guidelines for eligi-
bility have been established. One
of the guidelines states that
“explicit sexual imagery will not
be accepted.”

The guidelines define “explicit
sexual imagery” as anything that
depicts exposed sexual organs
and/or sexual intercourse.

“It was recommended by the

university attorneys,” said PPC
advisor Tom Misuraca.

“Last year we had some prob-
lems with some of the submis-
sions for the show," he said.. "We
ended up running into some legal
problems and decided to come
up with specific rules to better
monitor the submissions.”

Misuraca said the decision to
include these clauses was a joint
one between PPC and Pitt attor-
neys.

Last year’s art show had no reg-
ulations behind it. This year’s is
“closer to the correct way,"
according to Misuraca.

