By Barbara Merrin
For The Pitt News

The Student Health Service
will be distributing question-
naires to 1,500 Pitt students
this month inquiring about
their drug and alcohol use pat-
terns.

The questionnaire is part of a
comprehensive survey intended
to assist the Student Health
Service in developing needed
health education programs and
services on campus.

According to Dr. Shirley
Haberman of the Student
Health Service, the U.S.
Department of Education has
awarded them a grant for the
purpose of expanding sub-
stance abuse programs.
The grant is funding the survey
and any programs that are
developed as a result of the sur-
vey.

Haberman said the Student
Health Service has “periodically
conducted substance abuse sur-

veys in order to identify prob-
lems among Pitt students and
therefore do a better job of
designing programs responsive
to the students’ needs.” The
“Smart Cookie” facts that occa-
sionally appear in The Pitt News
are based upon the results of
their last survey.

The questionnaire was devel-
oped by the Student Health
Service and is partly based
upon Haberman’s dissertation
for her doctorate degree.

The students selected to par-
ticipate in the survey were cho-
sen through a computer-gener-
ated random selection process.
The students will respond to the
questionnaire anonymously,
and answers will be kept confr-
dennal

The four sections of the ques-
tionnaire include questions
about the student’s background,
current attitudes and behaviors
involving drugs and alcohol,
the frequency of use of various
substances and the student’s

experiences with drinking and
drug use.

, Some of the survey questions
deal with the problems that can
result from substance abuse,
including true/false statements
such as “I have physically hurt
myself or someone else when I
was drunk or ‘high”’ and “I
have changed courses or major
to avoid failing because of too
much ‘partying.”’

The Student Health Service
currently offers several pro-
grams for students with drug
and/or alcohol use problems.
The Personal Education
Assistance and Referral is most-
ly for students who have com-
mitted drug and alcohol viola-
tions, although some students
suspected to have problems are
referred to the program by
other students.

There are also support groups
for adult children of alcoholics
and for students recovering
from substance abuse. Smoking
cessation consultations are

available.

Along with the “Smart
Cookie” campaign, the Student
Health Service sponsors many
other awareness campaigns,
with representatives speaking
with fraternities, sororities and
athletes, and attending fresh-
man studies classes.

Haberman emphasized that it
is “important for students to
complete the questionnaire in
order to obtain an accurate pro-
file of students’ drinking and
drug use patterns and subse-
quently develop effective pro-
grams.”

She also said that responding
is necessary because some stu-
dents do not believe the results
of the “Smart Cookie” survey,
thinking that most Pitt students
are drinking or using drugs, an
idea not supported by the sur-
vey results.

