THE PITT NEWS, Tuesday, February 15, 1994

By Keith Pompey
Staff Writer

During the summer of 1990, Wes
Alexander, presently a junior hurdler for
Pitt, was sitting on top of the world.

But little did he know he would soon
start tumbling down.

He had just completed his junior sea-
son of high school track in which he fin-
ished second in intermediate hurdles at
the Virginia Track and Field State
Championships, thus ranking him as one
of the top ten scholastic 3OO—1neter hur-
dlers in the nation according to USA
Today.

For the next eight months, the only
thing on this 6-foot-1-inch kid’s mind
was to capture the state crown in the 300
hurdles.

“Basically my major goal throughout
my whole life, especially my senior year
[of high school], was based around win-
ning the state championship,” Alexander
recalled.

“It was something he wanted to do,”
Denise Alexander, Wes’ mother, said.
“He always spent time by himself always
concentrating on it.”

During that season, Alexander terror-
ized his competition as the No. 1—ranked
hurdler in the state.

Then on a sunny day, the moment
Alexander had been waiting for had
finally come —— in front of one of the
largest crowds ever assembled to watch
a high school state track and field cham-
pionship. '

As the gun sounded in the 300 hurdles,
the Green Run senior took off like a bat
out of hell. He had a 25-meter lead on
the rest of the field, with only 100 meters
to go.

That’s when the tragedy occurred. As
Alexander leaped the next hurdle, he fell
to the ground, breaking his arm and thus
shattering the life—long dream of being a
state champion.

“After I fell on the track, I sat there and
cried in front of all those people,”
Alexander recalls.

“Then for a month after that, I didn't
really eat a lot. I was basically a bad per-
son to people trying to be nice to me. I
really didn’t want to do anything but sit
in my room and watch TV as well as

ask myself ‘How could this happen to 

me?”

Maybe this was a blessing in disguise
because it forced Alexander, a student
who had always excelled in academics,
to think of life after track.

“After I came out of being depressed, it
made me realize that there is more to life
than track,” Alexander said.

“Going through high school, I never
thought that I would go through life not
running. But after I fell, I really had
that thought. And I realized if I’m not
going to run I better get my other stuff
together. Maybe by falling was good for
me.”

His grade point average went from a
3.4 in high school to a 3.7 in college,
while majoringsin communications with
the desire to go to law school.

Even though running isn’t the most
important thing in his life anymore, he
never stopped excelling on the track.

This year, Alexander returns as Pitt’s
most experienced hurdler. Last year at
the Big East Indoor Track and Field
Championship, he captured third place
in the 55 meter hurdlers (with a time of
7.70 seconds), as well as a third—place

